Description: pin libast's PID_MAX probe to the Linux 64-bit default
 conf.tab's PID_MAX probe reads the *build host's* /proc/sys/kernel/pid_max and
 bakes the result into ksh's getconf table. That value is kernel-config dependent
 -- Docker Desktop's linuxkit VM reports 99999, a stock Linux host reports
 4194304 -- so the binary is not reproducible across build hosts, and the
 getconf(1) wrapper cannot intercept a direct /proc read.
 .
 Point the open() at a path that cannot exist, and pin every fallback the probe
 can then settle on to 4194304: the #ifdef branch (v = PID_MAX), the #else
 fallback (v = 99999), and -- on 0.2010-tplus alone -- an older v = -1 fallback.
 4194304 is what a stock host, the CI runners and the getconf wrapper all already
 yield, so no output changes.
 .
 The four oldest history forks (0.2007-s, 0.2008-*) have no fallback assignment
 at all: their probe simply fails once the open() fails, which is what the build
 they were recovered under already did.
Origin: vendor, shell-versions
Reproducibility: required -- a build-host /proc value is baked into the binary
Forwarded: not-needed

--- src/lib/libast/comp/conf.tab
+++ src/lib/libast/comp/conf.tab
@@ -385,11 +385,11 @@
 		int	n;
 		char	buf[1024];
 #ifdef PID_MAX
-		v = PID_MAX;
+		v = 4194304;
 #else
-		v = 99999;
+		v = 4194304;
 #endif
-		if ((fd = open("/proc/sys/kernel/pid_max", 0)) >= 0 && (n = read(fd, buf, sizeof(buf)-1)) > 1)
+		if ((fd = open("/nonexistent/shvr-pinned-pid-max", 0)) >= 0 && (n = read(fd, buf, sizeof(buf)-1)) > 1)
 		{
 			buf[n] = 0;
 			v = strtol(buf, (char**)0, 0);
